  "assets": [
    {
      "assetId": "eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence/core_explanation/1",
      "kind": "core_explanation",
      "conceptId": "eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence",
      "title": "Letter-Sound Correspondence — core idea",
      "content": "Every English word is built from sounds (phonemes) that are represented in writing by letters or letter combinations (graphemes). Letter-sound correspondence (also called grapheme-phoneme correspondence, GPC) is the mapping between what you see on the page and what you say aloud. Reading requires this mapping in one direction (print → sound); spelling requires it in the other (sound → print). English has approximately 44 phonemes represented by 26 letters, meaning the mapping is many-to-many and must be learned explicitly.",
      "localKey": null,
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence.md",
        "startLine": 9,
        "endLine": 39
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence/learning_objective/1",
      "kind": "learning_objective",
      "conceptId": "eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence",
      "title": "Learning Objective",
      "content": "Given a simple English word (CVC, CCVC, or word with a common digraph):\n\n(a) the student correctly identifies each grapheme in the word (individual letters and two-letter digraph units);  \n(b) the student correctly produces the phoneme mapped to each grapheme;  \n(c) the student correctly blends the phonemes to decode the word.\n\n**Accuracy threshold:** 85% (aligned with foundational literacy standards and mastery_threshold).\n\n---",
      "localKey": null,
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence.md",
        "startLine": 39,
        "endLine": 51
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence/misconception/MC-1",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence",
      "title": "— Each Grapheme Has Exactly One Fixed Phoneme",
      "content": "### MC-1 — Each Grapheme Has Exactly One Fixed Phoneme\n\n**Observable symptom:** Student reads 'city' as /kɪti/; reads 'cycle' as /kaɪkəl/; insists 'c always says /k/.'\n\n**Diagnostic trigger:** DB-2a; TA-A04 P41.\n\n**Root cause:** Early phonics instruction often teaches single-letter sounds in isolation with a single keyword (a for apple, c for cat) without immediately teaching context-dependent variation. Students over-generalise the initial mapping.\n\n**Repair chain:** P27 (one-grapheme-one-phoneme belief) → P06 (concrete: three 'c' words) → P17 (contrast: cat/city) → P30 (context rule: what follows 'c' determines sound) → P31 → P42 (generate examples of each)\n\n**MAMR status:** Requires MC-4 cleared first. Rationale: if student is naming letters rather than producing sounds (MC-4), they cannot perceive or compare phonemes to notice context-dependent variation. MC-4 must be resolved before the student can benefit from context-sensitivity instruction.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-1",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-1"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence.md",
        "startLine": 5,
        "endLine": 19
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence/misconception/MC-2",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence",
      "title": "— Number of Letters = Number of Sounds",
      "content": "### MC-2 — Number of Letters = Number of Sounds\n\n**Observable symptom:** Student counts 4 sounds in 'ship' (s+h+i+p); counts 3 sounds in 'cat'; treats every written character as a separate sound unit.\n\n**Diagnostic trigger:** DB-2b; TA-A03 P41.\n\n**Root cause:** Visual scanning produces one-to-one mapping from letter to sound as a default. The grapheme concept (letter GROUP = single sound) must be explicitly taught; it is not intuitive.\n\n**Repair chain:** P27 → P07 (Elkonin boxes with digraph as single box) → P28 (say /s/ and /h/ separately — does that give 'ship'?) → P30 (count sounds, not letters; a grapheme can be 1 or 2+ letters) → P31 → P32 (5 words counting sounds correctly)\n\n**MAMR status:** Independent.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-2",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-2"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence.md",
        "startLine": 19,
        "endLine": 33
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence/misconception/MC-3",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence",
      "title": "— Silent Letters Are Irrelevant and Can Be Ignored",
      "content": "### MC-3 — Silent Letters Are Irrelevant and Can Be Ignored\n\n**Observable symptom:** Student reads 'cake' as /kæk/ (ignoring final e); reads 'knife' as /knaɪf/ (pronouncing the 'k'); ignores 'w' in 'write.'\n\n**Diagnostic trigger:** DB-2c; TA-B02 P41.\n\n**Root cause:** 'Silent' implies no function. Students interpret the term literally — if it makes no sound, it matters for nothing. The signalling function of silent letters (controlling adjacent sounds, indicating word origin) is not intuitive.\n\n**Repair chain:** P27 (silent = ignorable) → P06 (bit vs. bite: remove the e and word changes) → P17 (contrast: with/without the e) → P30 (silent letters = signalling letters; they control the vowel before them) → P31 → P32 (3 word pairs: bit/bite, cap/cape, hop/hope)\n\n**MAMR status:** Independent.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-3",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-3"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence.md",
        "startLine": 33,
        "endLine": 47
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence/misconception/MC-4",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "eng.phonics.letter-sound-correspondence",
      "title": "— Reading Means Naming Letters (Names ≠ Sounds",
      "content": "### MC-4 — Reading Means Naming Letters (Names ≠ Sounds)\n\n**Observable symptom:** Student says \"bee-ay-tee\" when asked to read 'bat'; uses alphabet names throughout decoding; \"reads\" by reciting letter names in sequence.\n\n**Diagnostic trigger:** DB-1; TA-A01 P41.\n\n**Root cause:** Alphabet instruction heavily emphasises letter names (the alphabet song, ABC books). The distinction between name and sound is never made explicit until formal phonics begins. Students assume the name IS the reading-sound.\n\n**Repair chain:** P27 (expose: reading = naming letters) → P06 (read 'bat' with names → \"bee-ay-tee\" — unrecognisable as a word) → P28 (conflict: nobody says \"bee-ay-tee\"; the word is 'bat' — names ≠ reading sounds) → P30 (reading requires sounds: /b/-/æ/-/t/ = 'bat') → P31 → P32 (5 words decoded with sounds, not names)\n\n**MAMR status:** FOUNDATIONAL for MC-1. Must be cleared before MC-1 repair. Rationale: context-sensitive phoneme variation (MC-1) requires the student to perceive different sounds for the same grapheme. A student still confusing letter names with sounds (MC-4) cannot perceive phonemic variation — they're producing names, not sounds, and cannot compare /k/ with /s/ as letter 'c' variants.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-4",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-4"
      ],
